Metrics Computation for the Occurrences Cube
of the Birds Directive Annex I

Data mobilisation from GBIF to the EBV Data Portal

Lina Estupinan-Suarez, Miguel Fernandez

German Centre for Integrative Biodiversity Research (iDiv)
lina.estupinans@idiv.de

2024-08-08

Introduction

In this notebook, we calculate simple metrics for the EU Annex I Birds Directive based on species occurrence in GBIF. For this, a bird occurrence cube (see Notebook 01 in this repository) was previously created using the occurrence cube software developed by GBIF under the Biodiversity Building Blocks for Policy (B3) Project. Details of the data query in GBIF are available at: doi: 10.15468/dl.43ydtq. We present five metrics below:

  • Total number of occurrences
  • Earliest month with records
  • Latest month with records
  • Month with the highest number of records
  • Month with the second highest number of records
  • Month with the third highest number of records

Note: This series of notebooks is part of the results of Task 3.3 of the Biodiversity Building Blocks for Policy Project funded by the European Unions Horizon Europe Research and Innovation Programme (ID No 101059592). Additional notebooks exploring the results and calculating simple metrics are also available in the same repository.

Metrics Computation

Metric 1: Total Number of Occurrences

We calculate the total number of occurrences for each species using the function total_occ.

# Calculate total number of occurrences per pixel
total_occ <- function(cin, gridin, coorin){
    
  # Find number of species
  spskey <- unique(cin[["data"]][["taxonKey"]])

  # Create empty raster
  r <- rast(ext(gridin), resolution=res(gridin), nlyrs=length(spskey), crs=crs(gridin))
  values(r) <- NA
  
   for (i in 1:50){ # length(spskey)
  print(i)
    # Subset one species
    spsi <- cin[["data"]][cin[["data"]]$taxonKey == spskey[i], ]

    # sum up the total number of occurrences per cellCode
    metricx <- spsi %>%
      group_by(cellCode) %>%
       summarize(total_occurrences = sum(obs), cellCode = first(cellCode))
    
    # Merge pixel coordinates with the corresponing EEA grid ID
    metriccoor <- merge(metricx[,c("total_occurrences", "cellCode")], coorin, by="cellCode")

    print(length(unique(metriccoor$x)))

    # Check for a few occurrences. Only 1 occurrence cannot be rasterised, and error extente when they are very few.
    if(length(unique(metriccoor$x)) < 10){
      # Add second empty point
      x <- metriccoor$x[1] + res
      y <- metriccoor$y[1] + res
      metriccoor <- rbind(metriccoor, c(NA, NA ,NA, x, y))
    }
  
  # Rasterize data
  r[[i]]  <- rast(metriccoor[,c("x", "y", "total_occurrences")], type="xyz", crs=crs(gridin), extent=ext(gridin))
    } 
  
  # Assign name of species key to the corresponding raster 'layer'
  names(r) <- spskey
  
  return(r)
}

Metric 2 and 3: Earliest and Latest Month of Occurrence at GBIF

We calculate the earliest (latest) month of occurrence for each species. The function min_max_month finds the earliest (or latest) month of records per species at the pixel level across the entire dataset.

min_max_month <- function(cin, gridin, coorin){
  # Find number of species
  spskey <- unique(cin[["data"]][["taxonKey"]])

  # Create empty raster for metric 2
  rmin <- rast(ext(gridin), resolution=res(gridin), nlyrs=length(spskey), crs=crs(gridin))
  values(rmin) <- NA
  
  # Create empty raster for metric 3
  rmax <- rast(ext(gridin), resolution=res(gridin), nlyrs=length(spskey), crs=crs(gridin))
  values(rmax) <- NA
  
    
  for (i in 20:50){  # length(spskey)
  print(i)
  # Subset one species
  spsi <- cin[["data"]][cin[["data"]]$taxonKey == spskey[i], ]

  # Convert date from character to numeric
  todates <- as.data.frame(str_split(spsi$yearMonth, "-", simplify = TRUE))
  colnames(todates) <- c("year", "month")

# Add year and month columns separate to the initial data
spsi$year <- todates$year
spsi$month <- todates$month

 # Calculate metric 2. In this example earliest month of record
    metric_min <- spsi %>%
      group_by(cellCode) %>%
      slice_min(month, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
      ungroup()

# Calculate metric 3. In this example earliest month of record
    metric_max <- spsi %>%
      group_by(cellCode) %>%
      slice_max(month, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
      ungroup()

  metricx_coor <- function(metricx, coorin, res){
    
    # Merge pixel coordinates with the corresponing EEA grid ID
    metriccoorx <- merge(metricx[,c("month", "cellCode")], coorin, by="cellCode")
    print(length(unique(metriccoorx$x)))

    if(length(unique(metriccoorx$x)) < 10){
      #add second empty point
      x <- metriccoorx$x[1] + res
      y <- metriccoorx$y[1] + res
      metriccoorx <- rbind(metriccoorx, c(NA, NA ,NA, x, y))
    }
    return(metriccoorx)
  }
  metriccoor_min <- metricx_coor(metric_min, coorin, res)
  metriccoor_max <- metricx_coor(metric_max, coorin, res)
  
  # Rasterize data
  rmin[[i]]  <- rast(metriccoor_min[,c("x", "y", "month")], type="xyz", crs=crs(gridin), extent=ext(gridin))

  # Rasterize data
  rmax[[i]]  <- rast(metriccoor_max[,c("x", "y", "month")], type="xyz", crs=crs(gridin), extent=ext(gridin))

  }

  # Assign name of species key to the corresponding raster 'layer'
  names(rmin) <- spskey
  names(rmax) <- spskey
  

  results_list <- list(earliest_month = rmin, latest_month = rmax)
  return(results_list)

}

Metrics 3, 4 and 5: Months with the highest, second highest, and third highest number of records

We identify the months with the highest (Metric 3), second highest (Metric 4), and third highest (Metric 5) number of records occurrences at GBIF.

maxrec_month123 <- function(cin, gridin, coorin){
  # Find number of species
  spskey <- unique(cin[["data"]][["taxonKey"]])

  # Create empty raster for metric 3
  r1 <- rast(ext(gridin), resolution=res(gridin), nlyrs=length(spskey), crs=crs(gridin))
  values(r1) <- NA
  
  # Create empty raster for metric 4
  r2 <- rast(ext(gridin), resolution=res(gridin), nlyrs=length(spskey), crs=crs(gridin))
  values(r2) <- NA
  
  # Create empty raster for metric 5
  r3 <- rast(ext(gridin), resolution=res(gridin), nlyrs=length(spskey), crs=crs(gridin))
  values(r3) <- NA

  i <- 1

  for (i in 1:30){  # length(spskey)
  print(i)
  # Subset one species
  spsi <- cin[["data"]][cin[["data"]]$taxonKey == spskey[i], ]

  # Convert date from character to numeric
  todates <- as.data.frame(str_split(spsi$yearMonth, "-", simplify = TRUE))
  colnames(todates) <- c("year", "month")

  # Add year and month columns separate to the initial data
  spsi$year <- todates$year
  spsi$month <- todates$month

  # Aggregate occurrences by cell and month
  month_occ <- spsi %>%
      group_by(cellCode, month) %>%
      summarize(total_occurrences = sum(obs), cellCode = first(cellCode))
      # ungroup()

 # Calculate metric 4. In this example earliest month of record
  metric4 <- month_occ %>%
      group_by(cellCode) %>%
      slice_max(total_occurrences, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
      ungroup()

  metricx_coor <- function(metricx, coorin, res){
    
    # Merge pixel coordinates with the corresponing EEA grid ID
    metriccoorx <- merge(metricx[,c("month", "cellCode")], coorin, by="cellCode")
    print(length(unique(metriccoorx$x)))

    if(length(unique(metriccoorx$x)) < 10){
      #add second empty point
      x <- metriccoorx$x[1] + res
      y <- metriccoorx$y[1] + res
      metriccoorx <- rbind(metriccoorx, c(NA, NA ,NA, x, y))
    }
    return(metriccoorx)
  }
  
  metric4_coor <- metricx_coor(metric4, coorin, res)
  # metric5_coor <- metricx_coor(metric5, coorin, res)
  # metric5_coor <- metricx_coor(metric6, coorin, res)
  
  # Rasterize data
  r1[[i]]  <- rast(metric4_coor[,c("x", "y", "month")], type="xyz", crs=crs(gridin), extent=ext(gridin))

  # Rasterize data
  # r2[[i]]  <- rast(metric5_coor[,c("x", "y", "month")], type="xyz", crs=crs(gridin), extent=ext(gridin))

  }

  # Assign name of species key to the corresponding raster 'layer'
  names(r1) <- spskey
  names(r2) <- spskey
  names(r3) <- spskey
  

  results_list <- list(month_with_highest_records = r1, month_with_2ndhighest_records = r2, month_with_3rdhighest_records = r3)
  return(results_list)

}
